export const story = {"seriesId":"field-day-fiasco","storyId":"field-day-fiasco","storyKey":"field-day-fiasco/field-day-fiasco","seriesTitle":"Field Day Fiasco","seriesDescription":"Casey Chen's parents take everything literally. EVERYTHING. So when they volunteer for school field day, every sports idiom becomes a disaster. Can Casey survive 'breaking a leg,' 'giving 110%,' and the dreaded tug of WAR?","title":"Field Day Fiasco","author":"Claude","description":"Casey Chen's parents take everything literally. EVERYTHING. So when they volunteer for school field day, every sports idiom becomes a disaster. Can Casey survive 'breaking a leg,' 'giving 110%,' and the dreaded tug of WAR?","ageRange":"7-10","genre":"Humor","tags":["literal","parents","sports","field day","idioms","family","humor"],"coverImage":null,"chapters":[{"id":1,"number":1,"title":"The Careful Way","file":"chapter-1.md","markdown":"# Chapter 1: The Careful Way\n\nMost kids wake up and say, \"I'm starving!\"\n\nI wake up and say, \"I am experiencing hunger and would appreciate breakfast at your earliest convenience.\"\n\nSee, my parents take things literally. And I mean *literally* literally. Not the way people usually mean literally, which is actually figuratively. My parents hear words and those words mean exactly what they mean.\n\nNothing more. Nothing less. Nothing in between.\n\nMy name is Casey Chen. I'm ten years old. And I have learned The Careful Way.\n\n---\n\nThis morning, I sat down at the breakfast table where Mom was reading a physics journal and Dad was sketching blueprints for something with way too many gears.\n\n\"Good morning,\" I said. \"I slept adequately and am now ready to consume food.\"\n\n\"Wonderful,\" said Mom, not looking up. \"Your cereal is in the cabinet. The milk is in the refrigerator. The bowl is—\"\n\n\"I know where everything is, Mom.\"\n\n\"Just being precise.\"\n\nDad finally looked up from his blueprints. \"Casey, your mother and I have exciting news.\"\n\nMy stomach dropped. In this house, \"exciting news\" could mean anything from \"we bought a new calculator\" to \"we're building a hovercraft in the garage.\"\n\n\"We volunteered to help at your school's field day!\" Mom beamed.\n\nThe spoon fell out of my hand.\n\n\"You... what?\"\n\n\"Field day!\" Dad said cheerfully. \"Running, jumping, throwing things. Physical education in a festive atmosphere. It sounds delightful.\"\n\nNo. No no no no no.\n\n\"When did you volunteer?\" I asked, trying to keep my voice calm.\n\n\"Yesterday. Principal Morrison said they needed parent helpers. We signed up immediately.\"\n\nI gripped the edge of the table. Field day was TOMORROW. There was no time. No time to prepare. No time to create a comprehensive list of phrases to avoid. No time to warn them about—\n\n\"Casey?\" Mom tilted her head. \"Your face is doing something unusual. Are you experiencing digestive distress?\"\n\n\"I'm fine,\" I squeaked. \"Totally fine. Everything is fine.\"\n\n---\n\nThat afternoon, I sat on my bed with a notebook and my best friend Malik on video chat.\n\n\"Just explain it to them,\" Malik said, munching chips. \"Tell them not to say weird stuff.\"\n\n\"It's not that simple.\" I was already scribbling. \"Do you know how many expressions people use in sports? Like, ALL of them. Break a leg. Kill it. Crush the competition.\"\n\n\"So?\"\n\n\"So my dad will hear 'crush the competition' and start worrying about which children are being crushed!\"\n\nMalik snorted. \"Your parents are hilarious.\"\n\n\"They're going to DESTROY me.\"\n\n\"See, that's exactly the kind of thing—\"\n\n\"I KNOW!\"\n\nI looked at my list. It was already two pages long and growing.\n\n**THINGS COACH THOMPSON WILL DEFINITELY SAY:**\n- Break a leg\n- Give it 110%\n- Kill it out there\n- Crush them\n- Knock 'em dead\n- Leave it all on the field\n- Throw in the towel\n- Hit it out of the park\n- Dig deep\n- Run like the wind\n\nI groaned. This was impossible.\n\n---\n\nAt dinner, I tried to prepare them.\n\n\"So,\" I said, pushing peas around my plate. \"About field day tomorrow.\"\n\n\"We're very excited,\" Mom said. \"I've prepared a spreadsheet of optimal hydration schedules.\"\n\n\"Great. That's... that's great. But here's the thing. Coach Thompson—he says things.\"\n\n\"Most people say things,\" Dad observed. \"That's how communication works.\"\n\n\"No, I mean—he says *expressions*. Phrases that don't mean what they literally mean.\"\n\nMy parents exchanged confused looks.\n\n\"For example,\" I continued, \"if he says 'break a leg,' he doesn't actually want anyone to break their leg. He's wishing them good luck.\"\n\n\"That's a very strange way to wish someone good luck,\" Mom said. \"Why not simply say 'good luck'?\"\n\n\"I don't know! It's just what people say!\"\n\n\"Inefficient,\" Dad muttered.\n\n\"And if he says 'give it 110%,' he doesn't actually expect—\"\n\n\"Well, of course not,\" Mom interrupted. \"That's mathematically impossible. The maximum effort one can give is 100%. To suggest otherwise would violate basic principles of—\"\n\n\"I KNOW. That's my point. People say it anyway. And I need you to just... go with it. Don't question it. Don't correct it. Just nod and smile.\"\n\nMy parents looked at each other again.\n\n\"We can do that,\" Dad said slowly. \"Nod and smile. Even when people are mathematically incorrect.\"\n\n\"Or medically dangerous,\" Mom added.\n\n\"Or medically dangerous.\"\n\nThey both nodded seriously.\n\nI wanted to believe them. I really did.\n\nBut I'd seen Dad try to \"go with it\" before. Last month, someone told him to \"hold his horses\" at the grocery store. He spent ten minutes looking for horses to hold.\n\nTomorrow was going to be a disaster.\n\nI could feel it in my bones.\n\n(Which, to be clear, is not a literal feeling. My bones feel normal. It's an expression.)\n\nMy parents would need that explained to them.\n\nI added it to the list.\n","narration":null},{"id":2,"number":2,"title":"Coach Thompson Opens His Mouth","file":"chapter-2.md","markdown":"# Chapter 2: Coach Thompson Opens His Mouth\n\nField day morning arrived like a freight train of doom.\n\n(Not an actual freight train. A metaphorical one. I'm getting good at these disclaimers.)\n\nThe field behind our school was transformed. Colorful flags flapped in the breeze. White lines marked racing lanes. Tables held ribbons and trophies and enough orange slices to feed an army.\n\nAnd there, right in the middle of everything, stood Coach Thompson with his megaphone and his polo shirt and his endless, endless supply of expressions.\n\n\"ALRIGHT, EVERYONE!\" he boomed. \"GATHER 'ROUND!\"\n\nStudents and parents shuffled toward him. I spotted Mom and Dad near the front, clipboards ready, matching sun hats on their heads. They'd arrived an hour early to \"ensure optimal preparation.\"\n\nI tried to catch their eye. *Remember what we talked about*, I thought desperately. *Nod and smile. Nod and smile.*\n\n\"Welcome to FIELD DAY!\" Coach Thompson bellowed. \"Today's the day we've been training for! Today we find out who's got what it takes!\"\n\nSo far, so good. Nothing weird yet.\n\n\"Now, I know some of you are nervous. But I want you to know—you've GOT this.\"\n\nMom leaned toward Dad. \"Got what?\" I heard her whisper. \"He didn't specify what they have.\"\n\nOh no.\n\n\"Just get out there and BREAK A LEG!\"\n\nEverything happened at once.\n\nMom's hand flew to her phone. \"I'm calling 911.\"\n\n\"LINDA, NO!\" I sprinted toward her, shoving past confused fourth-graders. \"It's an expression! EXPRESSION!\"\n\nDad was already looking around with concern. \"Which leg? Whose leg? This seems like a serious liability issue.\"\n\n\"Nobody is breaking any legs!\" I grabbed Mom's phone. \"He means good luck! It means GOOD LUCK!\"\n\nCoach Thompson, completely oblivious, continued: \"Now let's get out there and CRUSH THE COMPETITION!\"\n\nMom's eyes went wide. \"We will absolutely NOT be crushing any children.\"\n\n\"It's not real crushing!\"\n\n\"Kevin, did he just instruct us to crush children?\"\n\n\"It appears so. Should I contact the superintendent?\"\n\nOther parents were starting to stare. I could see my classmate Jordan's mom whispering to Jordan's dad. Great. Just great.\n\n\"Listen,\" I hissed, pulling my parents aside. \"Crush means WIN. It means win REALLY WELL. Nobody is getting crushed. Nobody is getting broken. These are just WORDS.\"\n\nMom took a deep breath. \"Okay. Okay. Words that don't mean what they mean. We discussed this. Nod and smile.\"\n\n\"Nod and smile,\" Dad repeated, nodding very seriously without smiling at all.\n\nCoach Thompson's megaphone crackled again. \"I want to see 110% out there today!\"\n\nThe nodding stopped.\n\n\"That's mathematically—\" Mom started.\n\n\"MATHEMATICALLY FINE,\" I said loudly. \"IT'S FINE.\"\n\n\"But the very concept of percentage—\"\n\n\"MOM.\"\n\nShe pressed her lips together. Dad was actually twitching.\n\n\"The maximum effort any individual can exert is, by definition, one hundred percent of their—\"\n\n\"DAD. PLEASE.\"\n\nMalik appeared beside me, grinning like this was the best day of his life. \"This is amazing,\" he whispered. \"This is the best field day ever.\"\n\n\"I hate you.\"\n\n\"LET'S KILL IT OUT THERE!\" Coach Thompson roared.\n\nBoth my parents gasped.\n\n\"KILL?\" Mom looked around frantically. \"Kill WHAT? Kevin, he wants us to kill something!\"\n\n\"Perhaps he means metaphorically kill our own limitations?\" Dad offered hopefully.\n\n\"NOBODY IS KILLING ANYTHING!\" I was definitely yelling now. Half the school was watching. \"It means DO WELL! These are SPORTS EXPRESSIONS! They're NOT LITERAL!\"\n\nCoach Thompson finally seemed to notice the commotion. He lowered his megaphone.\n\n\"Everything okay over there?\"\n\n\"Fine!\" I called back, my voice cracking. \"Everything's fine! Just clarifying some terminology!\"\n\n\"That's the spirit! Keep your head in the game!\"\n\nMom's hands flew to her head. \"IN the game? How would one insert a head INTO a game? That seems anatomically—\"\n\n\"EXPRESSION!\" I grabbed both their arms. \"Look. Just—just don't listen to anything Coach Thompson says. At all. Can you do that? Can you just pretend he's not speaking?\"\n\n\"That seems rude,\" Dad said.\n\n\"It's not rude. It's SURVIVAL.\"\n\nThe whistle blew. The first event was starting.\n\nThree-legged race.\n\nI looked at my parents. They looked back at me. Somewhere behind us, Coach Thompson yelled about leaving everything on the field.\n\nThis was going to be a long day.\n\n\"The three-legged race!\" an assistant announced. \"Parents, find your partners!\"\n\nMom and Dad stood next to each other, looking down at their legs.\n\n\"We already have four legs between us,\" Mom said thoughtfully. \"That seems sufficient. Why would we need only three?\"\n\n\"It's—\" I couldn't even finish. \"You know what? I'll explain after. Just... just go line up.\"\n\nThey walked toward the starting line, still discussing the mathematical inefficiency of reducing their collective leg count.\n\nMalik patted my shoulder. \"Hang in there, buddy.\"\n\n\"That's not a literal—\"\n\n\"I know.\" He grinned. \"I know.\"\n","narration":null},{"id":3,"number":3,"title":"The Events Begin","file":"chapter-3.md","markdown":"# Chapter 3: The Events Begin\n\nThe three-legged race was a disaster.\n\nNot because my parents were slow. Actually, they were incredibly fast. Once they understood the rules—that two people's adjacent legs get tied together to create a \"third leg\"—they approached it like an engineering problem.\n\n\"We need to synchronize our stepping cadence,\" Dad said, pulling out a small notebook. \"If we establish a rhythm of 1.2 steps per second—\"\n\n\"Agreed. I'll count prime numbers. You match my pace.\"\n\n\"Two! Three! Five! Seven! Eleven!\"\n\nThey shot down the field like a two-headed rocket, leaving other parents stumbling in the dust.\n\n\"WINNERS!\" Coach Thompson announced. \"Dr. and Mr. Chen take the three-legged race!\"\n\nFor one beautiful moment, I felt hope.\n\nThen the egg-and-spoon race started.\n\n---\n\nThe rules were simple: balance an egg on a spoon, walk to the finish line, don't drop the egg. If you touch the egg with your other hand, you're disqualified.\n\nMom stared at her egg. Then at the spoon. Then back at the egg.\n\n\"I'm not permitted to touch the egg.\"\n\n\"Correct,\" said the event coordinator.\n\n\"At any point.\"\n\n\"That's right.\"\n\n\"So if the egg begins to wobble, I cannot correct its position.\"\n\n\"You just have to balance it and—\"\n\n\"The optimal strategy, then, is to never move.\"\n\n\"What?\"\n\nMom planted her feet firmly. \"If I don't move, the egg cannot fall. Movement introduces variables. Variables introduce instability. Instability leads to egg displacement.\"\n\nShe became a statue.\n\nDad nodded approvingly. \"Sound reasoning.\"\n\n\"Ma'am, you have to WALK to the finish line.\"\n\n\"Do I? The rules stated I cannot touch the egg. You didn't specify a time limit.\"\n\nThe coordinator looked at me helplessly.\n\n\"Mom,\" I said through gritted teeth. \"The point is to get to the finish line BEFORE the other people.\"\n\n\"That wasn't stated explicitly.\"\n\n\"IT'S HEAVILY IMPLIED.\"\n\nShe didn't move. Her egg sat perfectly balanced on her perfectly still spoon.\n\nOther parents walked past her, eggs wobbling dangerously.\n\n\"This is so stupid,\" muttered someone's dad as his egg rolled off and splattered on the grass.\n\nMom's eye twitched. \"Stupid? He moved too quickly. The angular momentum of his arm swing created a pendulum effect. Any first-year physics student could have predicted—\"\n\n\"Mom. WALK.\"\n\nShe took one very slow, very careful step.\n\nThen another.\n\nThen froze again.\n\n\"The wind changed direction. I'm recalculating.\"\n\nMom came in last place.\n\nBut technically, her egg never fell.\n\n---\n\nThe relay race was next. This one seemed safe. Just running. Just passing a baton. What could go wrong?\n\n\"Hop to it, everyone!\" Coach Thompson called. \"Get to your positions!\"\n\nMom started hopping.\n\nActually hopping. Like a bunny.\n\n\"MOM. NO.\"\n\n\"He said hop to it. I'm hopping to it.\"\n\n\"It means HURRY!\"\n\n\"This IS hurrying. Hopping is a form of locomotion.\"\n\n\"Just WALK. Please. Regular walking.\"\n\nShe looked disappointed but resumed normal bipedal movement.\n\nThe race started. Dad was first. He ran well—engineers are surprisingly athletic when they treat running as a physics equation.\n\nMom was second. She took the baton perfectly.\n\nThen Coach Thompson yelled: \"RUN LIKE THE WIND!\"\n\nMom stopped.\n\n\"Linda?\" Dad called. \"Why did you stop?\"\n\n\"Wind doesn't run.\" She looked around, confused. \"Wind blows. It's the movement of air particles from high pressure to low pressure. It doesn't have legs. How can I run like something that doesn't run?\"\n\n\"JUST RUN!\"\n\n\"Should I blow? Is that what he means? Should I exhale forcefully while running?\"\n\nShe started running again, but also breathing out really hard, like she was trying to blow up a balloon while sprinting.\n\n\"HWOOOOOOO! HWOOOOOOO!\"\n\nPeople stared.\n\nA kid from the other team passed her easily.\n\nOur team came in third.\n\n---\n\nNext up: the sack race.\n\n\"Hop along in those sacks!\" the coordinator called. \"First one to the finish line wins!\"\n\nDad stared at his burlap sack.\n\n\"This is a sack.\"\n\n\"Yes.\"\n\n\"And we're racing.\"\n\n\"Yes.\"\n\n\"But you called it a sack race. Not a race while in sacks. A race for sacks. As in, competing to obtain sacks.\"\n\n\"Mr. Chen, please just get in the sack.\"\n\n\"But I already HAVE a sack. The race seems unnecessary if the prize is something I already possess.\"\n\nI buried my face in my hands.\n\n\"Sweetheart,\" Mom called from her sack, \"I believe we're meant to race WHILE INSIDE the sacks. It's a test of mobility under constrained conditions. Quite interesting from a biomechanics perspective.\"\n\n\"Ah!\" Dad's face lit up. \"A constraints-based competition! Why didn't you say so?\"\n\nHe hopped into his sack.\n\nThey actually won this one. It turns out when you approach sack-hopping as a mathematical optimization problem involving center of gravity and thrust vectoring, you can really move.\n\n\"HOP HOP HOP!\" Dad chanted, calculating angles mid-air. \"Forty-three degrees! Compensate for wind resistance!\"\n\n\"Peak thrust at the apex of each jump!\" Mom added.\n\nThey crossed the finish line three full seconds before anyone else.\n\nCoach Thompson was so surprised he just stared.\n\n\"That's... that's the fastest sack race I've ever seen.\"\n\n\"Thank you,\" Mom said, slightly out of breath. \"We optimized our bounce coefficients.\"\n\n---\n\nOkay. Maybe this wasn't going as badly as I thought.\n\nI mean, yes, there had been some awkward moments. Yes, my mom had stopped mid-race to debate the physics of wind. Yes, my dad had argued about sack ownership.\n\nBut we'd won TWO events!\n\nMaybe we could get through this.\n\nThen I heard Coach Thompson pick up his megaphone.\n\n\"ALRIGHT EVERYONE! LET'S HEAD TO THE FIELD EVENTS! I want you to LEAVE IT ALL ON THE FIELD! DIG DEEP! KEEP YOUR EYE ON THE BALL!\"\n\nI looked at my parents.\n\nThey were already reaching for their pockets.\n\n\"Leave what on the field?\" Mom asked.\n\n\"I don't have a shovel for digging,\" Dad added. \"Do they provide shovels?\"\n\nThe hope drained out of me.\n\nWe weren't even close to done.\n","narration":null},{"id":4,"number":4,"title":"Everything Falls Apart","file":"chapter-4.md","markdown":"# Chapter 4: Everything Falls Apart\n\n\"LEAVE IT ALL ON THE FIELD!\"\n\nThe words echoed across the grass. And my parents—my sweet, literal, extremely thorough parents—did exactly what they were told.\n\nDad started emptying his pockets. Keys. Wallet. A small notebook. Three pens. A calculator. A tape measure (because you never know). A granola bar. A backup granola bar.\n\nMom removed her watch. Then her earrings. Then she started untucking her shirt.\n\n\"Mom. MOM. STOP.\"\n\n\"But Coach Thompson said to leave it ALL on the field. All implies everything. I'm being thorough.\"\n\n\"He means effort! He means leave all your EFFORT on the field!\"\n\n\"That's not what he said.\"\n\n\"It's what he MEANT!\"\n\nDad was now trying to remove his shoes. \"Should I leave my socks too? He did say 'all.'\"\n\n\"NOBODY NEEDS YOUR SOCKS, DAD!\"\n\nOther parents were definitely staring now. Jordan's mom had her phone out, filming. This was going to be on the school Facebook page by lunch.\n\n\"Kevin, Casey seems distressed.\" Mom squinted at me. \"Your face is very red. Are you overheating? I have hydration schedules—\"\n\n\"I'm not overheating. I'm EMBARRASSED.\"\n\n\"Embarrassed?\" She looked genuinely confused. \"Why? We're following instructions precisely.\"\n\nI wanted to scream. I wanted to crawl into a hole. I wanted to be literally anywhere else on Earth.\n\nBut there was no time, because Coach Thompson was already shouting the next instruction.\n\n\"ALRIGHT, LONG JUMP! Keep your eye on the ball!\"\n\nThere was no ball.\n\nDad immediately started looking around. \"Where's the ball? He said to keep our eye on it, but I don't see—\"\n\n\"There's no ball in long jump!\"\n\n\"Then why did he mention a ball?\"\n\n\"BECAUSE PEOPLE JUST SAY THINGS!\"\n\nBut Dad wasn't listening. He'd found a kickball from the relay station. He picked it up. He pressed his eye directly against it.\n\n\"Am I doing this right?\"\n\n\"Kevin, your glasses are in the way.\" Mom adjusted his face. \"There. Now your cornea is making direct contact with the ball's surface.\"\n\n\"This seems unsanitary.\"\n\n\"It does. But those were the instructions.\"\n\nI couldn't take it anymore. \"THAT'S NOT—it means PAY ATTENTION! It means FOCUS! It doesn't mean LITERALLY PUT YOUR EYEBALL ON THE BALL!\"\n\nDad pulled his face away. There was a red ring around his eye from pressing too hard.\n\n\"You could have mentioned that earlier.\"\n\n---\n\nShot put was next. This required throwing a heavy metal ball as far as possible.\n\n\"DIG DEEP!\" Coach Thompson encouraged. \"SHOW ME WHAT YOU'VE GOT!\"\n\nDad looked at the ground.\n\nThen he started digging.\n\n\"Kevin, what are you doing?\"\n\n\"He said dig deep.\" Dad was scooping dirt with his hands. Mom had already started on her own hole. \"I assume there's something buried here? A prize perhaps? Treasure?\"\n\n\"THERE'S NO TREASURE! IT MEANS TRY HARD!\"\n\n\"Then why did he say dig? Casey, these expressions are extremely counterproductive. If he means 'try hard,' he should say 'try hard.' The reference to excavation is misleading at best.\"\n\n\"I KNOW. I KNOW! But normal people—\"\n\nI stopped.\n\nThe words hung in the air.\n\n*Normal* people.\n\nMom and Dad both looked at me. Something shifted in their faces.\n\n\"Normal people?\" Mom repeated quietly.\n\n\"I didn't mean—\"\n\n\"No, that's... that's fine.\" She brushed dirt off her hands. \"We understand. We're not normal.\"\n\n\"You wish we were normal,\" Dad added. He wasn't angry. He sounded... sad.\n\nAnd suddenly I felt terrible.\n\n\"That's not what I—I just meant—\"\n\n\"Casey.\" Mom put a hand on my shoulder. \"We know we're different. We've always known. We process language differently. We see the world differently. We can't help it.\"\n\n\"We try,\" Dad said. \"We really do. For you, we try to... nod and smile. Go with it. But sometimes we just hear the words as they are.\"\n\nI looked at them—my weird, wonderful parents who'd shown up an hour early with hydration schedules. Who'd calculated bounce coefficients to win a sack race. Who'd pressed their eyeball against a ball because someone told them to.\n\nThey weren't trying to embarrass me.\n\nThey were just being themselves.\n\n\"I'm sorry,\" I said. \"I didn't mean—\"\n\n\"HEY!\" Coach Thompson's megaphone blared. \"Final event in ten minutes! TUG OF WAR! Everyone to the main field!\"\n\nMom and Dad exchanged a look.\n\n\"Tug of... war?\" Mom said slowly.\n\n\"War.\" Dad's face was serious. \"That seems unnecessarily violent for an elementary school.\"\n\n\"Should we contact the authorities? War is a serious matter.\"\n\n\"Maybe we should talk to the principal—\"\n\n\"It's just a rope!\" I said quickly. \"You pull a rope! Two teams pull a rope! It's not an actual war!\"\n\nThey didn't look convinced.\n\n\"There are children here,\" Mom said. \"If there's going to be combat—\"\n\n\"No combat. Just rope.\"\n\n\"But he said WAR.\"\n\nI took a deep breath.\n\n\"Okay,\" I said. \"You know what? Never mind. You're right. The expressions are stupid. They don't make sense. 'Break a leg' is a weird thing to say. 'Dig deep' is confusing. 'Tug of war' does sound violent.\"\n\nThey stared at me.\n\n\"You're right,\" I continued. \"You've always been right. Normal people just ignore how weird language is. But you don't. You listen to what people actually say. And maybe... maybe that's not so bad.\"\n\nMom blinked. \"Are you feeling okay? Your face is still quite red.\"\n\n\"I'm fine.\" I grabbed both their hands. \"Come on. Let's go pull a rope together. As a family. And if Coach Thompson says anything weird, we'll just... ignore him. Together.\"\n\nDad smiled. \"That does sound nice.\"\n\n\"As a team,\" Mom agreed.\n\nWe walked toward the tug of war pit.\n\nI had no idea what was about to happen.\n\nBut at least we'd face it together.\n","narration":null},{"id":5,"number":5,"title":"Hold Your Ground","file":"chapter-5.md","markdown":"# Chapter 5: Hold Your Ground\n\nThe tug of war pit was chaos.\n\nParents lined up on both sides of a thick rope. Kids cheered from the sidelines. A mud puddle sat right in the middle, waiting for the losing team to get dragged through it.\n\nCoach Thompson stood between the two sides, megaphone raised.\n\n\"ALRIGHT! This is it! The FINAL EVENT! The TUG! OF! WARRRR!\"\n\nMom flinched at \"war\" but stayed in line. Progress.\n\nOur team was a mix of parents and kids. Mom and Dad were near the back, right behind Malik's dad (who'd been laughing quietly all day and gave me a thumbs up).\n\nThe other team looked strong. Really strong. They had Mr. Patterson, who coached the high school wrestling team. And Mrs. Williams, who did CrossFit. And three dads who all looked like they bench-pressed cars for fun.\n\n\"We're going to lose,\" Malik whispered beside me.\n\n\"Probably.\"\n\n\"Your parents gonna do something weird?\"\n\n\"Definitely.\"\n\nHe grinned. \"Good.\"\n\nCoach Thompson raised his hand. \"Teams READY!\"\n\nBoth sides grabbed the rope.\n\n\"On my whistle! Three! Two! One!\"\n\n*TWEEEEET!*\n\nBoth teams pulled. The rope went taut. Nobody moved.\n\n\"PULL!\" Coach Thompson yelled. \"PULL PULL PULL!\"\n\nMr. Patterson was red-faced, muscles bulging. Mrs. Williams had her feet dug into the grass. Slowly—very slowly—our team started sliding toward the mud.\n\n\"COME ON!\" Coach Thompson shouted. \"DIG IN! HOLD YOUR GROUND!\"\n\nI saw Mom's eyes widen.\n\n*Oh no.*\n\n\"HOLD YOUR GROUND!\" he repeated. \"DON'T GIVE AN INCH!\"\n\nSomething changed in my parents' faces. The confusion disappeared. In its place was... understanding. Determination. Purpose.\n\nThey had received an instruction.\n\nA very clear, very precise, very literal instruction.\n\n*Hold your ground. Don't give an inch.*\n\nMom planted her feet. Not just planted—ANCHORED. She shifted her weight, found her center of gravity, and became a statue.\n\nDad did the same. His engineering brain was calculating angles, friction coefficients, optimal weight distribution. He bent his knees exactly 23 degrees (I could practically see him measuring it mentally).\n\nThey stopped moving.\n\nNot just slowed down. STOPPED.\n\nThe rest of our team kept sliding, but Mom and Dad were frozen in place. Like someone had poured concrete around their feet.\n\nMr. Patterson pulled harder. The rope creaked. Our team slid another few inches.\n\nBut Mom and Dad didn't budge.\n\n\"What the—\" Mr. Patterson grunted.\n\nThe rope was bending around my parents. They'd become an anchor point. A fixed position in space. The rest of our team was being dragged forward, but Mom and Dad had decided they were not moving, and so they were NOT. MOVING.\n\n\"HOLD THAT GROUND!\" Coach Thompson bellowed.\n\n\"We are,\" Mom said calmly. \"Precisely zero inches have been given.\"\n\n\"I've calculated the optimal resistance,\" Dad added, not even straining. \"The force they're exerting is approximately 847 newtons. I'm counteracting with equal and opposite force. As Newton's Third Law dictates.\"\n\nOther parents on our team started to rally. Malik's dad dug in behind my dad. Other parents found their footing. The backward slide stopped.\n\nThen—slowly—we started pulling forward.\n\n\"WHAT'S HAPPENING?\" someone on the other team yelled.\n\n\"I don't know!\" Mr. Patterson was sweating now. \"They're not moving! Why aren't they moving?!\"\n\nCoach Thompson was going nuts. \"THAT'S IT! HOLD HOLD HOLD! DON'T GIVE THEM ANYTHING!\"\n\nMom looked at the inch of ground in front of her.\n\n\"I will not be giving anyone this ground. This is my ground. I am holding it.\"\n\nShe pulled.\n\nDad pulled.\n\nOur whole team surged forward.\n\nThe other team stumbled. Mrs. Williams' sneakers lost traction. The CrossFit muscles couldn't compete with the sheer, stubborn, *literal* willpower of two parents who had been told to hold their ground and were going to hold it until the sun burned out.\n\n\"PULL!\" someone on our team screamed.\n\n\"NOOOO!\" someone on their team screamed.\n\nAnd then—\n\n*SPLOOSH!*\n\nMr. Patterson went face-first into the mud puddle. Then Mrs. Williams. Then all three bench-press dads. One by one, the other team toppled, dragged forward by momentum and mud and the unstoppable force of my parents' refusal to give an inch.\n\n\"WE WON!\" Malik tackled me. \"WE ACTUALLY WON!\"\n\nThe crowd erupted. Kids swarmed the field. Our team dropped the rope, cheering.\n\nMom and Dad looked at each other.\n\n\"We held our ground,\" Mom said.\n\n\"Every inch of it,\" Dad confirmed.\n\n\"Well done.\"\n\n\"Thank you. You too.\"\n\nThey high-fived. It was the most robotic, precise high-five I'd ever seen.\n\nIt was perfect.\n\n---\n\nLater, after the ribbons were handed out and the orange slices were eaten and Coach Thompson declared it the \"best field day in school history,\" I found my parents by the parking lot.\n\nThey were covered in dust. Mom's hydration schedule was crumpled. Dad had lost two of his three pens.\n\n\"Hey,\" I said.\n\n\"Hello,\" Mom said. \"You seem less red than before.\"\n\n\"Yeah.\" I smiled. \"I'm feeling better.\"\n\n\"We apologize for the confusion earlier. The expressions were—\"\n\n\"Forget it.\" I hugged her. Then Dad. \"You were amazing.\"\n\n\"We were?\"\n\n\"You held your ground. You didn't give an inch. You won us the tug of war.\"\n\nMom and Dad exchanged looks.\n\n\"We just followed the instructions,\" Dad said.\n\n\"Precisely as stated,\" Mom added.\n\n\"I know.\" I grinned. \"That's what made it work.\"\n\nAs we walked to the car, Malik ran up beside us.\n\n\"Dude! Your parents are LEGENDS! Did you see Patterson's face? Covered in mud! And your dad—he was like a ROBOT! An UNMOVABLE ROBOT!\"\n\n\"Thanks?\"\n\n\"I'm gonna tell EVERYONE. 'Casey's parents take everything literally and it's AWESOME!'\"\n\nHe sprinted off.\n\nMom tilted her head. \"Is being a 'legend' a positive thing? Legends are typically historical figures who—\"\n\n\"It's positive, Mom.\"\n\n\"Ah. Good.\"\n\nWe got in the car. Dad started the engine.\n\n\"So,\" he said, \"how was field day?\"\n\nI thought about it. The panic. The embarrassment. The hopping and the digging and my dad's eyeball pressed against a ball.\n\nBut also the sack race victory. The tug of war triumph. The way they'd held their ground—really, truly, literally held it—and won.\n\n\"It was good,\" I said.\n\nAnd I meant it.\n\nLiterally.\n\n---\n\n### The End\n\n*P.S. — Next week is the school spelling bee. Mom has already prepared a presentation on the history of English etymology and why silent letters are \"orthographically dishonest.\"*\n\n*I'm bringing earplugs.*\n\n*But also... I can't wait.*\n","narration":null}],"chapterCount":5,"audio":null,"narration":{"hasNarration":false,"chapters":[]},"assets":[],"standalone":false};
